    {
        "content": "<p>You can't apply hn because the hypothesis of hn doesn't match h, there's an extra <code>succ</code> in <code>h</code>.</p>",
        "id": 451332011,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1720944055
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The hypothesis of hn is more general than h. I thought I can still apply it (like apply a value of a subtype to a function).</p>",
        "id": 451332483,
        "sender_full_name": "B YI",
        "timestamp": 1720944438
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No, both <code>hn</code> and <code>h</code> are statements about a <em>specific</em> number <code>nn</code> in your context. They do not say \"for all numbers nn...\".</p>",
        "id": 451332702,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1720944608
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Got it. Thanks.</p>",
        "id": 451332781,
        "sender_full_name": "B YI",
        "timestamp": 1720944701
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you had a number <code>x</code> in your context and also a proof <code>hx : x = 37</code> then you would not be able to deduce that all numbers were equal to 37. It's the same phenomenon here.</p>",
